"# Appendix — The Verbs Cookbook

Notes on drum-kit playback via `synth/kit`. Verified against `bin/motoi eval`.

---

## Drum kit hit: `synth/kit`

`synth/kit patch step?` plays one hit from the internal drum kit. `patch` is a symbol naming which drum to hit; `step` is an optional integer identifying which step of a pattern the hit belongs to (defaults to zero). Returns the symbol `'ok` on success, or `'error` if the audio engine is unavailable.

```scheme
(synth/kit)                             ; => ok    (default patch, defaults to 440Hz fallback)
(synth/kit 'kick)                       ; => ok
(synth/kit 'snare)                      ; => ok
(synth/kit 'hat)                        ; => ok
(synth/kit 'kick 3)                     ; => ok    (kick, on step 3 of a pattern)
```

The built-in patch names are `'kick`, `'snare`, `'hat`, `'crash`, `'clap`. Unknown patches still play — they fall back to a 440Hz tone marked with the requested patch name — which is convenient during development but a bug to catch before ship. If a beat is not landing on the drum you expect, check the patch name first.

Under the CLI harness the audio engine is a no-op, so every call returns `'ok` without producing sound. In a browser host with the audio engine wired up, each call triggers the corresponding synth-model hit.

The `step` argument is a hint — some engines use it to skip re-triggers when a step has already fired this bar. In CORE it is stored and available to the engine; how the engine uses it is implementation-defined.

---

## Chord playback: `synth/chord`

`synth/chord notes dur?` plays a list of MIDI note numbers together as a chord. `dur` is the duration in seconds; defaults to 0.5. The notes argument must be a proper list — `(list 60 64 67)` or `'(60 64 67)`. Passing a non-list returns the symbol `'error` without touching the audio engine; a valid list dispatches into the audio engine and returns `'ok` if the engine accepts the notes, `'error` if it does not.

```scheme
(synth/chord 'not-a-list)                       ; => error   (arg-shape guard)
(synth/chord '(60 64 67))                       ; => error   (headless CLI: no audio adapter)
(synth/chord (list 60 64 67))                   ; => error   (same reason)
```

Under the CLI harness the audio engine is not wired and every real dispatch returns `'error`. In a browser host with the audio engine installed, `(synth/chord '(60 64 67))` starts a C major triad — all three notes at the same cursor position, sustained for `dur` seconds.

The chord verb rewinds the audio cursor between notes so they truly overlap rather than playing sequentially — this is the difference from calling `note/strike` in a loop.

---

## Downbeat rounding: `land-on-downbeat`

`land-on-downbeat beat` rounds a fractional beat value to the nearest whole beat. Used by scheduling code that wants an event to snap to the next downbeat rather than land off-beat.

```scheme
(land-on-downbeat 3.7)                          ; => 4
(land-on-downbeat 3.4)                          ; => 3
(land-on-downbeat 0)                            ; => 0
(land-on-downbeat 2.5)                          ; => 3
```

The verb is pure — no clock, no state. Pass in the beat position you *would* be at without snapping; get back the beat position you *want* to be at.

---

## Closing note

Every example in this appendix was checked against `bin/motoi eval` on 2026-07-17. `'ok` from the CLI does not mean sound emerged from your speakers — it means the verb was dispatched. Wire an audio host to hear anything.
")
